96
00:06:09,573 --> 00:06:13,783
And my workflow evolved step
by step, slowly, but it did.

97
00:06:14,423 --> 00:06:18,973
First, I ask AI to build, then
I ask to build using MVVM,

98
00:06:19,053 --> 00:06:20,453
some architecture patterns.

99
00:06:20,883 --> 00:06:23,253
Then I ask it to reuse
existing components.

100
00:06:23,563 --> 00:06:25,273
Then add architecture rules.

101
00:06:25,743 --> 00:06:29,353
And later, I start asking to
explain decisions before coding.

102
00:06:29,413 --> 00:06:32,673
The more experience I gain, the
less freedom I gave to the model.

103
00:06:33,073 --> 00:06:36,803
That sentence is probably
the main lesson of this talk.

104
00:06:36,813 --> 00:06:43,093
You need to… The less freedom you gave
to the model, the better code would be And

105
00:06:43,253 --> 00:06:48,453
in terms of the enterprise project because
the issues there was a bit different.

106
00:06:49,063 --> 00:06:53,513
In a large enterprise code
base, I cannot be the architect.

107
00:06:53,683 --> 00:06:54,973
The architect is already there.

108
00:06:55,593 --> 00:06:58,713
The problem is not that it
writes obviously bad code.

109
00:06:58,933 --> 00:07:02,893
Often the code makes sense in
isolation, but reduction code that

110
00:07:03,043 --> 00:07:05,473
does not live in that isolation.

111
00:07:05,993 --> 00:07:10,153
There may be several ways to solve
the same problem in a large project.

112
00:07:10,643 --> 00:07:14,973
Some are modern, some are legacy, some
are load only in specific modules, and

113
00:07:14,973 --> 00:07:17,383
some should not be applied anymore.

114
00:07:18,003 --> 00:07:21,253
Finding the right approach is a
developer's responsibility, and

115
00:07:21,253 --> 00:07:26,323
it's super important for you to
know which approaches are existing.

116
00:07:26,913 --> 00:07:31,763
Because without that context, AI may
generate code that looks reasonable but

117
00:07:31,763 --> 00:07:33,873
would not pass a serious code review.

118
00:07:34,373 --> 00:07:36,043
I also saw over-testing.

119
00:07:36,483 --> 00:07:40,863
Unit or UI tests that are technically
valid but too complicated, too

120
00:07:40,863 --> 00:07:44,803
implementation-specific or not
variable enough, and, it's taking

121
00:07:44,803 --> 00:07:48,083
energy to validate them, and it's
taking energy to run them again

122
00:07:48,083 --> 00:07:49,423
and again during compilation time.

123
00:07:49,423 --> 00:07:53,233
So you need to be very careful
with what AI is testing, because

124
00:07:53,363 --> 00:07:55,023
AI to write a lot of code.

125
00:07:55,673 --> 00:07:58,153
Another risk is stress plus AI.

126
00:07:58,323 --> 00:08:02,733
When you are under pressure, it is
tempting to accept code you do not

127
00:08:02,743 --> 00:08:06,983
fully understand because it works and
it looks like perfect implementation.

128
00:08:06,983 --> 00:08:10,213
But there is… can be a lot of issue.

129
00:08:10,243 --> 00:08:15,973
It may call internal libraries correctly
and to reduce your ownership, but at the

130
00:08:15,973 --> 00:08:20,223
end of the day, later, when something
need to be changed or fixed you will

131
00:08:20,253 --> 00:08:26,023
pay the price because debugging will
take a lot of time But enterprise

132
00:08:26,063 --> 00:08:27,533
is not the one that had issues.

133
00:08:27,543 --> 00:08:30,983
Also, we have our indie projects, right?

134
