screen and different on another one.

190
00:11:56,073 --> 00:12:00,193
As Android developer, I could recover
from this because I know the platform,

191
00:12:00,253 --> 00:12:04,493
architectural patterns, coroutines,
compose, testing, and common failure

192
00:12:04,493 --> 00:12:07,043
modes, because again, years of experience.

193
00:12:07,303 --> 00:12:10,533
But if someone builds an app with
AI without the domain knowledge,

194
00:12:10,723 --> 00:12:13,383
the speed can become a trap.

195
00:12:13,523 --> 00:12:17,723
My rule now is simple, do not
allow code you cannot explain.

196
00:12:17,733 --> 00:12:21,953
If you see an unfamiliar function,
library call, or architectural

197
00:12:21,953 --> 00:12:24,523
decision, stop and understand it.

198
00:12:24,953 --> 00:12:26,293
Ask AI to explain it.

199
00:12:26,383 --> 00:12:27,673
That's pretty easy.

200
00:12:27,733 --> 00:12:29,943
AI know context better than you sometimes.

201
00:12:30,553 --> 00:12:31,403
Take notes.

202
00:12:31,553 --> 00:12:32,763
Add the lessons.

203
00:12:32,763 --> 00:12:39,033
You can add a lessons MD to your project
and mention it there, or add rules,

204
00:12:39,073 --> 00:12:41,043
memories, whatever suits you better.

205
00:12:41,523 --> 00:12:46,483
The extra ten percent of time spent
understanding can save days of debugging

206
00:12:46,673 --> 00:12:49,803
later And that's it with the problems.

207
00:12:49,893 --> 00:12:53,983
So let's jump to the solutions,
because for each problem

208
00:12:53,993 --> 00:12:55,203
we can find the solutions.

209
00:12:56,023 --> 00:13:00,023
And the first one would be build
context before implementation.

210
00:13:00,883 --> 00:13:03,363
So the first solution is in context.

211
00:13:03,753 --> 00:13:07,193
The better examples you give to the
model, the better output you get.

212
00:13:07,363 --> 00:13:08,773
This sounds obvious, right?

213
00:13:09,063 --> 00:13:13,493
But in practice, it changes the
developer workflow, development workflow.

214
00:13:14,003 --> 00:13:17,253
Before implementation, analyze
similar models, if we're

215
00:13:17,253 --> 00:13:19,253
talking about the big projects.

216
00:13:19,773 --> 00:13:22,413
Find how the same problem
was solved before.

217
00:13:22,463 --> 00:13:26,523
Check which tools are used, what
is legacy, what is deprecated, and

218
00:13:26,523 --> 00:13:28,403
where trade-offs are acceptable.

219
00:13:28,893 --> 00:13:32,773
Then save this knowledge in model
memory, project notes, architectural

220
00:13:32,773 --> 00:13:35,073
documents, or your own daily notes.

221
00:13:35,363 --> 00:13:36,923
It feels slow, yes.

222
00:13:37,373 --> 00:13:41,143
You will want to skip it and just
implement the feature, but that extra

223
00:13:41,143 --> 00:13:47,043
hour of understanding project the next,
will save the next ten hours for you.

224
00:13:47,623 --> 00:13:52,523
A good workflow is notes,
understanding, plan, implementation.

225
00:13:52,873 --> 00:13:55,493
Do not ask AI to write code first.

226
00:13:55,573 --> 00:13:58,253
Ask it to understand the
system first, summarize the

227
00:13:58,253 --> 00:13:59,643
patterns, and propose a plan.

228
00:14:00,063 --> 00:14:05,933
Only then let it generate the smallest
reasonable change Solution number two.

229
00:14:06,553 --> 00:14:08,923
Remove AI freedom with rules.

230
00:14:09,123 --> 00:14:11,223
Yeah, freedom is bad in our case.

231
00:14:11,723 --> 00:14:14,483
The second solution will be
removing necessary freedom.

232
00:14:14,973 --> 00:14:17,623
In the project, this is especially
important because there is

233
00:14:17,623 --> 00:14:21,273
no existing code base, so AI
can write whatever it wants.

234
00:14:21,853 --> 00:14:23,003
So you need to constrain the model.

235
00:14:23,843 --> 00:14:25,833
Create rules before the
project becomes big.

236
00:14:25,993 --> 00:14:31,273
And here's like a few practical
ru-rules that you can use.

237
00:14:31,893 --> 00:14:36,983
Choose the architecture, MVVM,
MVI, clean architecture, or

238
00:14:37,263 --> 00:14:38,553
whatever fits your product.

239
00:14:39,113 --> 00:14:42,393
Define package structure like
data, domain, presentation.

240
00:14:42,743 --> 00:14:45,883
Define libraries for core
responsibilities, coroutines,

241
00:14:45,883 --> 00:14:50,153
dependency injection, networking,
persistence, background work.

242
00:14:50,433 --> 00:14:54,333
Define how repositories,
services, handlers, managers,

243
00:14:54,373 --> 00:14:56,053
and so on should be used.

244
00:14:56,213 --> 00:14:59,393
Where are you using them, and
which one should be singleton,

245
00:14:59,453 --> 00:15:01,153
which one is not, and so on.

246
00:15:01,173 --> 00:15:02,173
That's super important.

247
00:15:02,953 --> 00:15:07,303
Define error handling, Toast, Sn
acknowledgementBar, popup, inline,

248
00:15:07,313 --> 00:15:09,603
maybe some wrappers for that, up to you.

249
00:15:10,213 --> 00:15:13,713
Define navigation, bottomSheet,
screens, dialogues.

250
00:15:13,873 --> 00:15:16,503
Again, you are the one who
will need to choose that.

251
00:15:17,133 --> 00:15:21,213
Define offline behavior because
adding offline later will be

252
00:15:21,263 --> 00:15:24,863
close to impossible or just super
painful if you will do it with AI.

253
00:15:25,363 --> 00:15:27,793
Define light and dark theme expectations.

254
00:15:28,033 --> 00:15:32,213
Very often, AI just like missing
this part and not adding any

255
00:15:32,213 --> 00:15:33,433
styles for the second one.

256
00:15:33,983 --> 00:15:38,053
Store these rules in files
like rules MD, architecture.

257
00:15:38,053 --> 00:15:42,823
I said about this before, so choose
the one you like more or just memory.

258
00:15:43,273 --> 00:15:45,033
Cloud codecs, whatever you need.

259
00:15:45,783 --> 00:15:48,663
So yeah, at the end of the
day, freedom sounds creative.

260
00:15:48,923 --> 00:15:52,273
In AI-assisted development,
freedom is expensive.

261
00:15:52,853 --> 00:15:58,433
Good constraints are not bureaucracy,
they are product safety next one.

262
00:15:58,563 --> 00:16:02,783
About the test that I said before,
AI to write a lot of tests.

263
00:16:02,813 --> 00:16:10,143
So AI made the testing much easier,
but easier does not always mean better.

264
00:16:10,423 --> 00:16:14,603
Enterprise of work test
coverage matters because small

265
00:16:14,603 --> 00:16:16,953
changes can impact many users.

266
00:16:17,303 --> 00:16:22,343
I can generate UI tests, unit tests, edge
cases, and regression tests super quickly.

267
00:16:22,873 --> 00:16:24,553
But it can also over-test.

268
00:16:24,683 --> 00:16:28,823
I saw tests that were complicated,
fragile, not very meaningful.

269
00:16:29,503 --> 00:16:32,783
The solution is to give the
model a strict testing prompt.

270
00:16:33,283 --> 00:16:35,643
Explain what a good test
means in your project.

271
00:16:35,683 --> 00:16:39,333
Ask for behavior-focused test,
not implementation-focused test.

272
00:16:40,033 --> 00:16:44,603
Ask it to avoid testing private
details or duplicating production

273
00:16:44,613 --> 00:16:46,243
logic inside assertion.

274
00:16:46,743 --> 00:16:50,093
After a few iterations, turn those
preferences into reusable testing rule

275
00:16:50,103 --> 00:16:53,963
or skill, and basically it will solve
everything for you with just one skill.

276
00:16:54,473 --> 00:16:55,993
But always review the basics.

277
00:16:56,323 --> 00:16:58,433
Does the test name match
what it actually verifies?

278
00:16:58,433 --> 00:17:00,733
Did the test fail to the right reason?

279
00:17:01,203 --> 00:17:06,223
A useful-- useless test generated
quickly is still useless, remove it.

280
00:17:06,223 --> 00:17:12,883
AI reduces the cost of writing tests,
but developers still own test quality.

281
00:17:13,383 --> 00:17:17,573
Another one, super important for
the indie projects, it's build

282
00:17:17,633 --> 00:17:20,063
core UI before the features.

283
00:17:20,563 --> 00:17:25,758
For AI-assisted Android development,
a core UI module is one of the highest

284
00:17:25,788 --> 00:17:27,788
return investments you can make.

285
00:17:28,348 --> 00:17:32,368
Before building dozens of screen,
define colors, typography, radios,

286
00:17:32,418 --> 00:17:37,048
spacing, standard buttons, text
fields, loaders, alerts, bottom sheets,

287
00:17:37,098 --> 00:17:42,398
error pop-ups, back buttons, bills,
drop-downs, and navigation animations.

288
00:17:42,468 --> 00:17:46,218
That's everything that I faced in my app.

289
00:17:46,228 --> 00:17:49,638
So you can add your own,
but that's the base.

290
00:17:50,428 --> 00:17:54,688
This is useful in any app, but with
AI, it becomes even more important.

291
00:17:55,028 --> 00:18:00,658
If the basic decisions are already
made, AI stops inventing them.

292
00:18:00,818 --> 00:18:04,778
It reuses, it follows, it becomes
faster and more consistent.

293
00:18:05,658 --> 00:18:10,318
In Logi, Logia, users love
the UI, and AI made fancy UI

294
00:18:10,318 --> 00:18:11,838
dramatically easier to implement.

295
00:18:12,278 --> 00:18:16,248
But the best results come when the
model has a design system to work with.

296
00:18:16,688 --> 00:18:22,138
Screenshots are still extremely useful,
especially when recreating an iOS-oriented

297
00:18:22,148 --> 00:18:25,018
design in Compose, what was my task.

298
00:18:25,608 --> 00:18:27,808
But screenshots alone are not enough.

299
00:18:27,848 --> 00:18:31,198
Each screenshot will be
interpreted by AI differently.

300
00:18:31,948 --> 00:18:36,728
So a screenshot tells AI what to
build, a design system tells AI how

301
00:18:36,768 --> 00:18:39,148
your product should behave everywhere.

302
00:18:39,498 --> 00:18:44,688
So this is super important to build
a core UI module at the beginning.

303
00:18:45,188 --> 00:18:52,468
And what AI still cannot do for you
because AI is still not super powerful.

304
00:18:53,198 --> 00:18:55,708
AI is a very strong technical tool.

305
00:18:55,758 --> 00:18:59,798
With good prompts, it can implement
tasks at a high level, but it

306
00:18:59,808 --> 00:19:01,928
does not replace product thinking.

307
00:19:01,968 --> 00:19:06,728
That's why I put this guy at the
beginning, AI took our jobs, but in

308
00:19:06,728 --> 00:19:11,838
reality, product thinking is getting
more and more important, and this is

309
00:19:11,838 --> 00:19:17,288
why I think development still will
be on top, at least for a few years.

310
00:19:17,998 --> 00:19:22,248
So with a good prompt, it can implement
a task at a high level, but it

311
00:19:22,258 --> 00:19:23,858
does not replace product thinking.

312
00:19:24,368 --> 00:19:27,278
It does not see the full
product picture the way you do.

313
00:19:27,718 --> 00:19:31,408
It does not understand how users
feel when an animation is slightly

314
00:19:31,428 --> 00:19:35,878
too slow, when a button feels wrong,
or when a feature technically works

315
00:19:35,878 --> 00:19:39,698
but does not solve the real user
problem, and it's up to you to do that.

316
00:19:40,268 --> 00:19:44,118
It doesn't know which legacy system
is still there for a reason, which

317
00:19:44,118 --> 00:19:48,798
trade-off is acceptable, or when you
should push back on a requirement.

318
00:19:49,238 --> 00:19:51,558
I think this is where
development is moving.

319
00:19:51,628 --> 00:19:55,098
We are becoming product developers,
not only coding developers.

320
00:19:55,538 --> 00:20:00,518
Our value is in trade-offs,
alternative pushback, architecture,

321
00:20:00,568 --> 00:20:04,368
technical depth, and connecting
product needs with technical reality.

322
00:20:04,948 --> 00:20:09,278
The more context you have, the better
your cooperation with AI becomes.

323
00:20:09,498 --> 00:20:14,488
AI can write the code, but you still
need to decide what code should exist.

324
00:20:14,988 --> 00:20:20,368
And getting close to
finale, what do we have now?

325
00:20:20,868 --> 00:20:22,938
My role did not become smaller.

326
00:20:23,068 --> 00:20:24,258
It just changed.

327
00:20:24,748 --> 00:20:29,298
Delivery increased, but the need to
have for control increased with it.

328
00:20:29,688 --> 00:20:32,488
You can validate product
ideas faster than before.

329
00:20:32,658 --> 00:20:34,168
You can build UI faster.

330
00:20:34,278 --> 00:20:35,818
You can write tests faster.

331
00:20:36,218 --> 00:20:37,398
You can ship faster.

332
00:20:37,658 --> 00:20:42,028
But you can also lose
ownership super faster.

333
00:20:42,408 --> 00:20:45,748
You can get lost in generated
code that works but does not

334
00:20:45,768 --> 00:20:47,028
belong to your architecture.

335
00:20:47,428 --> 00:20:51,968
You can end up with a product that moves
fast for two months and then become

336
00:20:51,968 --> 00:20:55,868
painful to maintain, and you will need
to just rewrite the whole project.

337
00:20:56,448 --> 00:21:00,048
The main lesson is to teach AI and
learn yourself at the same time.

338
00:21:00,488 --> 00:21:03,978
Do not sacrifice understanding
in the race for delivery.

339
00:21:04,228 --> 00:21:05,208
It's hard, I know.

340
00:21:05,328 --> 00:21:08,078
It's hard to push back,
but it's the price you pay.

341
00:21:08,688 --> 00:21:10,798
You control the process, not the model.

342
00:21:11,138 --> 00:21:14,318
AI is a tool that can move you to
a completely different level of

343
00:21:14,328 --> 00:21:19,738
development, or it can create a
code base you no longer control.

344
00:21:19,988 --> 00:21:21,198
The choice is still yours.

345
00:21:21,518 --> 00:21:27,288
That is also why I would not present AI as
a junior developer that simply needs task.

346
00:21:27,378 --> 00:21:30,398
I see it more as a very
fast production multiplier.

347
00:21:30,768 --> 00:21:33,288
If your process is clear,
it multiplies clarity.

348
00:21:33,528 --> 00:21:36,098
If your architecture is
messy, it multiplies mess.

349
00:21:36,328 --> 00:21:39,518
If your product vision is strong,
it helps you reach it faster.

350
00:21:39,838 --> 00:21:45,058
If your vision is vague, it will generate
a lot of code around the vagueness.

351
00:21:45,558 --> 00:21:49,878
And just to summarize what we
discussed before if I need to do it

352
00:21:49,898 --> 00:21:53,478
in one sentence, it would be this:
The more experience I gain, the

353
00:21:53,478 --> 00:21:55,878
less freedom I gave to the model.

354
00:21:56,228 --> 00:22:00,568
That may sound strange in the current
AI hype cycle, where everyone talks

355
00:22:00,568 --> 00:22:02,618
about giving agents more autonomy.

356
00:22:03,038 --> 00:22:08,388
But in production engineering, autonomy
without cost on context becomes risk.

357
00:22:09,078 --> 00:22:11,388
AI did not make me write less code.

358
00:22:11,558 --> 00:22:14,878
It made me responsible for
more code than ever before.

359
00:22:15,108 --> 00:22:19,388
And that is why understanding ownership,
architecture, and product thinking

360
00:22:19,648 --> 00:22:22,188
matter more than they ever did.

361
00:22:22,648 --> 00:22:25,398
Shipping AI feature that do
not break in production is not

362
00:22:25,398 --> 00:22:27,098
about trusting the model more.

363
00:22:27,528 --> 00:22:31,718
It's about designing the system,
the workflow, and the constraints,

364
00:22:31,898 --> 00:22:36,528
so users do not have to care how
unpredictable the model can be.

365
00:22:37,328 --> 00:22:39,558
This is the mindset I
want to leave with you.

366
00:22:40,548 --> 00:22:43,708
Do not ask how much code
AI can generate for you.

367
00:22:44,058 --> 00:22:48,668
Ask how much reliable, understandable,
maintainable product you can ship

368
00:22:48,668 --> 00:22:51,018
with AI while still keeping ownership.

369
00:22:51,018 --> 00:22:56,198
This is a much harder question
and also a much more useful one.

370
00:22:56,698 --> 00:23:01,818
So yeah, build a good project, improve
your product thinking, improve your

371
00:23:01,888 --> 00:23:06,568
technical skills, and you will still
be on a tap top of development.

372
00:23:07,438 --> 00:23:11,458
Good luck with your journey, and
thank you for your attention.

